Here are both approaches for .NET MAUI Shell navigation:

**1. Register the route**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate from ProductListPage**
```csharp
// Approach A – pass a simple string ID
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");

// Approach B – pass the full object via a dictionary
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    ["product"] = selectedProduct   // complex object, not serialized to the URI
});
```

**3. Receive data with `IQueryAttributable` on the ViewModel**
```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty] private Product _product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A – simple string parameter
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
        {
            var id = idObj.ToString();
            // load from a service, cache, etc.
            Product = _catalogService.GetById(id);
        }

        // Approach B – full object passed through the dictionary
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
        {
            Product = p;
        }
    }
}
```

**4. Wire the ViewModel to the page**
```csharp
public partial class ProductDetailsPage : ContentPage
{
    public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = vm;
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param (A) | Object param (B) |
|---|---|---|
| **Passed via** | URI query string | `IDictionary<string, object>` overload |
| **Deep-link safe** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (object isn't in the URI) |
| **Serialization** | Automatic (string) | None needed; passed by reference |
| **Best for** | IDs, flags, simple values | Large/complex objects already in memory |

Both approaches arrive in the same `ApplyQueryAttributes` method, so you can support either (or both) in one ViewModel.
